134. Ascanius is compared to a jewel set in gold, or to ivory set in wood.

136. - Notice the prosody: (l) the hiatus, the ο of buxo being unelided, (2) the four-syllabled word at the end of the line. Both points are imitations of the Greek use, and are often employed by Verg. to impart variety to his verse. Box-wood is of a deep yellow-brown, terebinth of a rich black eolour, thus both are well adapted for inlaying with ivory.

143. pristina] Mnestheus drove back Turnus, ix. 778 ff. pulsi 'rurm gloria] ‘the glory consisting in the rout of Turnus.’ The participle pulsi refers not so much to the person acted on as to the act itself, and is to be rendered by a substantive in English : it means not ‘ Turnus having been routed,' but ‘the rout of Turnus’ (R. 560). Cp. inf. 504, intactum Pallanta, ‘the leaving alone of Pallas'; ii. 413, ereptae viminis ira, ‘wrath at the rescue of the maid'3 ii. 643, captae urbi, ‘the capture of the oity.'
